Jeremy Bee (bee@sfu.ca) wrote:

: The HPFS in OS/2 is all 16 bit, and some other stuff as well.  16 bit code is
: not that big a deal actually, in both OS/2 and Win95, it is usualy finely
: tuned machine level code.

Yes, but the OS/2 16-bit code works in protected mode and is fully reentrant.
This means OS/2 will NEVER switch to real mode once the kernel is loaded.
On the other hand, Win95 has 16-bit REAL mode code and switches to real mode
when running programs.  This seems to be real problem with running slow on
the P6. Not so much 16-bit but rather real mode, non-reentrant code.

Plus, the new HPFS has been recoded in C for portability (but not necessarily
32-bit) and will be available in the next version of Warp.  This means that
it could be switched to 32-bit easily once OS/2 supports 32-bit IFS.

And speaking about file systems, last week at Comdex in Toronto I saw
OS/2 for PPC and they were running FAT. They said HPFS and NTFS would be
available with the released product so it appearse that they are not using
JFS as someone suggested here some time ago.

: Jeremy

