Maybe I wasn't too clear there.  I know the 16 bit code that remains is
mainly for compatibility reasons, but all the stuff that was replaced was
replaced in the areas that would most affect performance.  It's the
standard trade-off between compatibility and performance, with stability
thrown in for good measure.  As to the effect on performance of the 16 bit
code, I meant software performance.  I thought I said this explicitly but
maybee that was in another post.  The performance hit on the P6 is because
of *any* 16 bit instructions passed through the chip as far as I
understand, so where the 16 bit code is in the software doesn't really
affect that.  There is not much of a reason to run Win95 on a P6 however,
and I think that whole issue is a boondoggle of sorts.  If I was a
computer store salesperson and I was selling a computer with a P6,
